[1] Cholera, probable - Dominican Republic (Bahoruco Province)
Date: Mon 31 Dec 2013
Source: Ecos del Sur [in Spanish, trans. Mod.JG, edited]
http://www.ecosdelsur.net/2012/12/posible-brote-de-colera-afecta.html


A diarrheal disease initially considered as amebiasis by healthcare workers in San Bartolome Hospital, but diagnosed as cholera by Dr Liz Perez, is currently affecting many persons in Galvan [Bahoruco Province], and more than 50 people have been admitted to the hospital since 25 Dec 2012.

Even though authorities in San Bartolome Hospital considered these cases were a simple outbreak of amebiasis, Dr Liz Perez, attending physician in the Oral Rehydration Unit of this hospital, declared that the gastrointestinal symptoms (watery diarrhea and moderate to severe dehydration) of all cases correspond to an infection caused by _Vibrio cholerae_, which presents as an intestinal infection.

Dr Perez pointed out that, on 24 and 25 Dec 2012, more than 25 cases of this disease were taken care of, and this weekend [29-30 Dec 2012], a similar number of persons are presenting to the hospital with the aforementioned symptoms, and since they have common features, the condition has been defined as 'clinical cholera'.

"Because of their clinical condition and a fall in blood pressure, severe dehydration, foul-smelling and rice-water stools, we think we are facing cholera cases," said Dr Perez, who insisted that authorities should warn citizens about this condition, specifically in Las Piedras, La Zabila, La Guama, and other communities in the high areas of Galvan municipality.

She pointed out that patients are admitted in a special area, where they receive parenteral and oral therapy, as well as some medications, and they are observed in the ward until they are discharged. Dr Perez urged persons living in Galvan municipality to chlorinate water for daily use, especially if they get it from brooks or small streams, in order to prevent the occurrence of more cases of this disease that already has affected more than 50 persons.

She also mentioned that this educational effort must be led and reinforced by the Ministry of Health, in order to prevent further spread of this disease, which although apparently no deaths have been reported (yet), is a very risky condition.

[Byline: Ramon Antonio Medina]

